How to finance a green transformation.
New York—World leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations this week to assess the global war on climate change and submit new emissions pledges.
The climate crisis is a pressing issue, and our pace of action is far from sufficient.
We can't seem to shift into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires cooperation and joint efforts from both the public and private sectors.
Fortunately, thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaboration to mitigate climate change is increasing.
Under the leadership of the UN Secretary-General's Special Envoy on Climate Action Michael Bloomberg, CFLI was established, with the aim of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
This month, the CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," which lists ways to expand green finance to support orderly low-carbon economic transformation, and proposes public-private cooperation opportunities to achieve the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement targets.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the world's largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects.
However, at the call of the heads of state and government of the European Union and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Von der Leyen, we are now ready to take on greater ambitions and strengthen the role of the EIB as the EU's dedicated climate bank.
The European Investment Bank will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investment, and will invest at least €1 trillion in low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, at least 50% of EIB financing will be used for climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will rationalize all of our financing activities to align with the objectives of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will eliminate energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help various economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our task is to invest in Europe's future, and the most important issue at hand is climate change.
The urgency of the climate crisis is as strong as our resolve.
This summer, Europe has been hit by record-breaking heatwaves and crop failures, which is a result of last year's drought.
Many developing countries have similar experiences.
Flooding and other climate-related phenomena cost billions of dollars each year for major cities, and threaten the lives of even more people.
However, the climate crisis is also an opportunity, because providing funding for new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce the air pollution that plagues cities around the world.
Changing investment patterns can accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has begun.
Market forces increasingly favor clean energy, shifting away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, nearly half of the U.S. coal-fired power plants retired, while the clean energy industry created 3.3 million jobs, compared with just under 100,000 in the coal industry.
In addition, an increasing number of American cities and states have pledged to achieve net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from the Beyond Carbon initiative, launched last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies, which aims to support the full decarbonization of the US economy.
As a member of the international community, we not only need to invest in clean energy, but also need to reduce investments in dirty energy.
In reality, with fossil fuel subsidies, we are still spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investments towards electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive green transformations.
These investments will yield huge returns, including massive savings in the huge costs to public health from air pollution.
In addition to that, we can also take many measures to guide the necessary funds.
First, we must improve the standards for data and disclosure.
For a long time, businesses and investors have been unaware of climate-related risks and have not known the rationality of reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather impacts.
It's starting to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in a more sustainable way, and enabling investors to reward companies that take climate change seriously.
Secondly, we must clarify the investment risks related to green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few developing world cities can obtain credit ratings.
However, the total investment in clean buses, energy-efficient buildings, and other emissions-reducing projects was affected.
The government and listed banks must step up efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including adopting the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led with the Bloomberg Philanthropies Foundation.
Third, we need to implement the modernization of the power grid.
Refunds and tax incentives and other incentives have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for enterprises and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar plans, speed up the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, and speed up solving the intermittent problem.
In addition, better grid connectivity can allow areas with surplus wind and solar power to supply areas in short supply.
The government can play a leading role in these two areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, since then the green bond market has grown to $136 billion.
Compared to the global bond market of $100 trillion, this is a drop in the ocean.
Consequently, the EIB is helping the EU develop sustainable finance standards classification, so that investors can compare like-for-like projects, just as with standard bonds.
More information about carbon footprint investment will enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby driving more private investment towards low-carbon projects.
This is the way we provide financing for green transition.
